Pale Horse, Pale Rider: Who and what makes a Unicorn in North America?¶

Project One¶

Introduction¶

Determining the success of a startup and enacting policies that would support startups are important for North American policy makers. Having a strong startup economy, especially in R&D fields are vital in signaling a nation’s innovative power, improves the economic conditions of high skilled workers and others, and most importantly to investors can provide greater lucrative opportunities. As a result, many economists from academia and professional investors to find the factors most relevant in determining the success of a startup.

From academia, the significance of the startup economy in the last few decades has led to numerous articles and studies published on the subject. Academic interest in startup specific models and analysis have developed recently, much of the research being done from the 1990s. However, studies on understanding companies and business structure are well established. The articles selected for this paper will draw from both types of studies. Broadly, the literature could be categorized into three groups: determinants that led to success and methods in valuation.

Ratzinger et al. (2018) investigates the impact the education of the founder has of achieving a investment milestone. Using a probit regression, Ratzinger et al. (2018) finds that at all levels of a university education (referred to as a technical education), there was a statistically significant increase in the likelihood that a startup reached a milestone. This paper seeks to apply these findings to all members of the founding team of a startup, and understand the impact that the quality of each team member’s education has on the overall performance of the startup. This will be done by averaging the university ranking of each team member and giving a ’brain power’ index for each startup.

Baum et al. (2000) discusses the role of network size and inter-organizational alliances that gives startups in the Canadian Biotech sector access to industry specific knowledge, a stable exchange relationships and innovative capabilities, external endorsement, and the perceived quality and reliability of its goods and services. After testing these results, they found alliances with pharmaceutical companies, universities, research institutes, and marketing companies experienced higher rates of patenting and growth in revenue. An alliance with a 5% increase in the number of pharmaceutical company alliances at founding was found to increase the number patents by 1%. In this paper, the generalized importance of network size will be investigated outside the biotech sector alone.

Valuating a startup is different from a valuating an established company, as many early stage startups will not be able to provide the accounting information needed to make an accurate assessment. Miloud et al. (2012) argues that the three main methods of evaluating a startup were industry organization and value, the resources of the startup, and the value of it’s network. The literature presented in Miloud et al. (2012) mention the importance of the growth of the industry itself and its impact on the valuation of companies. After controlling for all other factors, a 20 percentage point increase on average increased 0.11% increase in pre-money valuation of a company. This study shows the importance of controlling for industry specific change in my own analysis.

This paper adds to existing literature by finding factors that make a ”unicorn” startup in North America. A Unicorn startup is defined to be a startup with an estimated valuation of US $1 billion. Although there were an abundance of determinants that were provided in the existing literature, the network size and the average quality of education of the team members will be considered the most important factors that determine the success of a startup after controlling for geographic and year fixed effects.

Data Source and variables¶

The data used for research comes from Cirtautus (2020), which is a Kaggle dataset that had many potential determinants that can be used for analysis. In the cleaning process, Bernard (2016) had the Times Higher Education dataset that would be merged to form the The dataset includes a wide range of startups that were created between 1901 to 2014. This would cause some issues in processing the data, as many well known brand companies would be included in our analysis. For example, companies such as General Motors and Hewell and Packet (now known as HP) would be included with early stage startups. Further cleaning had to be done as much of the data would include incorrect information or missing entries that complicated the research. It was challenging to find well written documentation on how the data was collected that the described each variables in detail. However by processing the data, merging other public datasets, and web scraped data, this paper would have enough relevant and accurate information that would be useful for analysis. After processing the data, there were 22,700 startups that were used for our multivariate linear regression.

The Kaggle dataset had a lot of missing entries or unclear entries for each variable that it seemed necessary to document how these variables were processed. The missing entries for the dependent variable - the valuation of a startup - is understandable as many of these companies are private corporations. These issues, which in economics is referred to as ”information asymmetry”, can be the source of biased analysis if not addressed correctly. One issue that stem from information asymmetry that is discussed in HEALY make citation is from biased estimation and analysis from financial intermediaries and analysts. This paper, which utilizes big data tools and analytics, requires accurate reporting in order to make unbias and accurate assumptions. With incorrect and/or missing information, potentially useful variables can be undervalued. For many of the independent variables, the number of missing entries were low, and were therefore dropped without much loss in data.

As this paper’s focus is on the valuation of a startup, it was necessary to construct this information with some of the data that was available. The estimated valuation data, which is the sum of the total acquisition price, the IPO valuation, and the amount raised in funding. Total acquisition price required the most processing, as acquistions worked in two directions. Many of the startups that are acquired are acquired by other ’startups’. A few of the ’startups’ that have acquired the most are CISCO, google, Microsoft, IBM, Yahoo!. For simplicity, both the acquiring and acquired company would add to their value, as it can be assumed that both companies have had some value added as a result of acquisition: the acquiring company gains a potential technological/innovative edge and reduced competition whereas the acquired company is paid a lump sum of money from a larger corporation. The IPO valuation data and amount raised added in it’s original form from the kaggle dataset.

The X variables of interest are the following:

  • brain power
    • The dataframe will include the average research score provided by the Times Higher Education list of 2016. Although the observations do not include companies founded after 2014, for the purpose of our analysis we will assume that there is not much variation between the research capabilities of the institutions after 2000. THe reason 2016 was selected is because there is a greater number of universities included in the 2016 dataset.
  • network size
    • The network size is the total number of people in the people.csv dataset that are affiliated with each startup.
  • number of milestones
    • This was a long string variable, which describes in detail important moments in the startup's development. It can be assumed that if a company has a greater number of these recorded 'milestones', then it is more likely to be successful. However, what exactly constitutes a 'milestone' according to this dataset has not been made clear, so it is likely this variable is a weaker indicator.
  • Tax credit rate
    • The amount of tax incentives that are provided by the municipal governments in Canada and the US.
  • Industry Clusters
    • A variable that can be considered are the industry that a startup is categorized as. Controlling for this will allow us to see which cities have the capital and policies necessary for startups to survive in. An industry cluster will most likely form around cities, with most of these cities having other prominent industry clusters forming around them. A few well known examples of startup clusters would be the Cambridge/Boston Biotech 'hotbed' or Silicon valley for software startups.
  • quarter
    • We can use the quarters to assess how a startup preforms as a quarter compared to other quarters.
  • real GDP (quarter)
    • Entry into the market is extremely important for a SU, as the success of a startup in the earliest stages largely hinges on its ability to survive. If the economy is performing poorly such as in during a recession, the cost of maintaining a startup and the difficulty in securing funding will effectively be crushed. For this project, the indicator which was used to determine the economy's performance is the real GDP of the economy, which was downloaded from the Federal Reserve of St Louis (FRED) website. It is important to note that the real GDP per quarter has been adjusted to 2012 US dollars, and is in billions of dollars. Because this dataset lists quarterly real GDP, it was necessary to convert the existing dataset's 'created_at' dates into quarters.
  • category_code
    • The dataset has up to 44 different categories that an startup can fall into (i.e. software, web, biotech, etc). Different categories are likely to see varying degrees of success. Therefore, category_code seemed important to include, as controlling for this will help us understand the general performance of all startups.
  • age
    • A variable that can be useful in the future, it would primarily serve as a control variable with regression analysis as company's that are older are likely to be more 'successful'. This is problematic however, as not controlling for this variable might lead to regression coefficients that are uninutitive and inaccurate. For example, experts may say market entry is an important factor for a SU, however with companies like General Motors, IBM, and other highly established "startups" will be assumed to have been created in extremely poor economic conditions (low real GDP quarter), and will lead to extreme biases that can impact the findings of this project.
    • This may only be used in Project two for mapping purposes. In future developments of this project, quarter will likely be used as it contains more detailed information.

def uni_clean(lst):
    """Return a cleaned list for uni_key"""
    result = []
    for elm in lst:
        if isinstance(elm, tuple):
            result.append(elm[0])
        else:
            result.append(pd.NA)
    return result

lst = list(degrees["uni_key"])
save = uni_clean(lst)
degrees["uni_key"] = save

Much of the literature about the success of a startup discusses the importance of individual entrepreneurs and their relationship with each other. However, this project will focus primarily on the "brain_power" and network size of the startup, as these variables are likely to capture some of the positive effects that come with entrepreneurship. Many successful entrepreneurs can be assumed to be highly educated individuals (or at least are able to recruit many highly educated individuals), as well as having a greater network size at their disposal.

An important metric to understand a startups value is through the money the company raises through IPOs. A company that goes public through an IPO technically no longer qualifies as a Unicorn startup, as a Unicorn by definition is a private company that is valued over US $1 Billion. However, for startups that are publicly traded, IPOs give us the best estimate of the valuation of a company, as investors and financial institutions investigate the true worth of the company. Therefore, it is important to include this information in our cleaned dataset.

Finally, we will be cleaning the startup dataset. The startup dataset has two columns named "created_at" and "founded_at", with no clear description on the difference between the two dates. However, as can be seen above, there are much more missing date entries for the "founded_at" column. Displaying the startup quickly shows that there are some observations that are contained in the "founded_at" column that would otherwise be missing in the "created_at" column. Furthermore, the "created_at" column only contains companies founded in the last couple decades, whereas the founded_at column includes dates that range from 1901 to 2014. Therefore, the "founded_at" column will be assumed to be the primary column, and all the missing date entries will be replaced with the "created_at" columns date entries.

def dig(df, name, find):
    """Return a the name of a specific startup from a data frame. Most likely will only be useful for
    startup dataset
    """
    for i in range(len(df[name])):
        if find == df[name][i]:
            return df['name'][i]

The second problem present in the acq data set was briefly addressed in the introduction. Both the acquiring and acquisitioned startups will be given the acquisition price amount. Startups that are acquiring large amounts of other startups will therefore be given the sum total of all the acquisitioned price amounts. It can be assumed that this is a fair measure of success, as in the case of these 5 companies it demonstrates that they have enough existing capital to acquire over a hundred startups, while also absorbing the innovative ability of the acquired into their own work force.

In later sections, the total acquired price will also be added to the estimated value of a company, as the amount raised through acquisitions can be assumed to add additional value to their company.

Therefore, it is necessary to get the sum total of all the values of a given object_id (both acquiring and acquired), and combining the values of both columns to create a singular column to extract the total_acquired_price.

One challenge in using real GDP in the startup dataset is that there are 666 empty entries in the GDPC1 column. This is because there are startups on this startup dataset that were founded 1901, decades before the world governments were measuring GDP to assess macroeconomic performance (for context, some of the US industrialists reponsible for the creation of some of the companies in this dataset were born during the US civil war).

However, addressing this issue is unclear: a complete exclusion of these powerful established startups will remove some of the most powerful North American startups in the startup dataset. But including them will undoubtedly create biases. For the Project one and two, these data entries will be incldued, however in the last part of the data cleaning section, a column stating the decade which the startup was founded in will be created that can allow us to control for this data in useful ways.

Although the next addition is not an X variable, in order to understand North American businesses we must include a country code. In order to do this, the startup dataset must first be merged with the location dataset with only the necessary columns: object_id and country_code.

The startup dataframe will also be merged with the location dataframe, which will become useful for Project Two, the ipo dataframe that has our main dependent variable, and finally the hr_df, which contains the network size and brain power index.

In [ ]:
location = location[["object_id", "country_code"]]
startup = pd.merge(startup, location, on = 'object_id', how = 'left', copy=False)

startup = pd.merge(startup, hr_df, on = "object_id", how="left", copy=False)

At this point, the money raised through IPO and the valuation amount combined acted as an estimated worth of a startup. Some companies that have not had an IPO can still find funding from private investors, which also adds to the value of the company. As mentioned earlier, total acquisition price will also be included in the total valuation of a company. Therefore, we will combine all the columns into a singular valuation column.

In [ ]:
# Combining the est_value from IPO with funding_total_usd to proxy for the startups 'valuation'
startup.est_value.fillna(0, inplace=True)

startup.drop(columns = ["est_value", "total_acquired_price", "funding_total_usd"], inplace=True)

We will also create dummy variables for unicorn and established 'startups'. Established startups can threaten the validity of our findings, as companies that were established before the 2000s and are established brands will be unlikely to behave the same way as modern startups. Established startups that are highly valued will also skew the results, and will therefore have to be excluded in the final project.

In the code above, we have merged the startup and num_miles together. With this startup dataset, we have merged all the necessary information into a singular dataset that can be analyzed effectively. In addition, the empty values in num_miles, category_code, and country_code have been filled with 0, "UNLISTED", and "NO_COUNTRY" respectively. Having no value for "num_miles" implies that the startup has no milestones (according to the milestones dataset). Because "category_code" is a discrete value, it will presumably fine to have a singular tag for them. Unless there are non statistical errors or direct data manipulation (such as the creators of this dataset purposefully excluding category tags of startups in specific industries), this should not lead to any biases. For similar reasons, country_code missing data has been filled with an arbitrary label.

Brain power and network size has the most significant number of missing data entries. It is unlikely however that a company has no network whatsoever, as this would imply there are startups in the dataset that somehow exist without a founder or any workers. As a result, for the purpose of our regression we will assume that every startup has at least a network size equal to one, which would mean the only network the startup has at its disposal is the owner themselves.

We cannot make any assumptions however on brain power itself. This is because brain power is based on the average research score of the university as provided by the Times Higher Education ranking. Therefore, we will handle these missing entries by replacing them with zero.

From this summary statistics table most of the variables are clearly not normally distributed. Intuitively, it would make sense for normality to not exist for these companies, as there will be a handful of highly successful startups which will dominate the market in all three of these aspects (especially with the established startups still included in this dataset, normality can not be assumed). This is most apparent in valuation, as the highest value startup will have a worth two million times greater when compared to the 75th highest value startup. Because of the potential issues of biases that could exist especially in companies that are older and more established, the final regression results exclude these established startups entirely.

It is important to note that the oldest class of established startups are outliers in terms of their average funding and make far more than the other startups in the rest of this dataset. As a result, the time series will begin at 1944 Q1 to exclude the established startup outliers, as including it impacts the visual aide the timeseries can otherwise provide. Observable from this time series is that the average valuation for startup cohorts varies greatly, even with the outliers excluded from the time series. Generally speaking, startups that were created between 1969 to the mid 1980s had the highest levels of average valuation, with there being four notable peaks in average funding for startups in this period. It may be useful to plot this data in a different way, using real gdp as an x variable.

The folowing will be a scatter plot, which will allow us to mark every entry of the dataset (startups founded during and after 2000Q1), making it easier to visualize the distribution of each of these periods. If there are less startups being founded during the same period, then the initial hypothesis that a smaller number of highly successful companies were founded between 1999 and 2009 is true. Because we are using scatterplot, the y variable will be converted into log values. As a result, any startup that did not receive any funding will be excluded from the plot. The Message¶

The main goal of this paper is to understand the extent to which the brain power, network size, number of milestones, and tax credit rate impact the value of a startup company. Although the first three variables were processed and extracted from Cirtautus (Cirtautus), the tax credit rate needs the necessary geographic information for it to be used in later analysis. In the final project, many of these determinants are in fact useful in understanding the value of a company. For example, in the final regression, an increase in brain power by a percentage point will increase the value of a company by 0.8%. Similarly, a 1% change in network size on average increased the value of a company by 0.48%.

Maps and interpretation¶

Many of the maps that will come in this section to my surprise look almost indistinguishable to each other. Prior to this project, I truly believed that there existed 'special zones' for many of these startups and we would be able to see a disporportianate amount of startups of one type cluster in specific regions in the US. Although this information is perhaps anecdotal for an academic project, my own intership had to do with researching news reports about the Biotech sector in the US and I was under the impression that Biotech was such a specialized sector that only a select few cities in the US had a booming sector that was leading the world in this. However, at least with the maps produced, this view seems to have been highly exaggerated. For future developments, I will investigate my own work further to see if there are ways to perhaps visualize this more effectively (Since there are too many dots in major cities, it is quite possible that the viewer just perceives all of these clusters as one shapeless blob after another).

With that aside, much of the data is still very interesting as we can see the presence of a select group of industries in each North American city, as well as view the greater number of SU entry that occurred in NA. Potential Data to scrape¶

There are many potential datasets that can be merged with the current dataset to further explore exactly what factors are most important in determining a startups success. With web scraping, it may be possible to concat more updated information about each of the determinants listed in the previous projects (i.e. updating the list of North American startups post-2014, scraping websites/social media to update the number of milestones for existing/new startups, scraping business journal's to see update startup acqusition data, etc). However, there are new determinants and proxies that could help us understand a succecssful startup. With the possibility of web scraping, new determinants and variables that we can include in our dataset can include asset valuation, GPS locations of universities, and public perception data.

To be considered a Unicorn startup (a concept that is hinted at the title of my project), a startup must have assets valuing over $1 billion USD. This is the most accurate piece of data that is completely missing from the Kaggle dataset, which was proxied by the total funding USD variable in the earlier versions of this project. However, total funding by investors and government agencies are not the sole way that a company can rapidly increase it's value, as it does not include any information about the revenue of the company. With data scraping, this project can have a better Y-variable (total funding being reduced to another x-variable), and this project will actually be able to understand the trends that increase the chances of creating unicorns. We can scrape this data from websites like Yahoo! Finance, and try to create a dataframe with the relevant information.

With webscraping techniques, we can collect the ranking and GPS location of every university in North America, which can be used to approximate the distance between a startup's headquarters from the nearest univeristies. This can add to the clustering information, as many R&D centers in America are likely based near university clusters. This means that being closer to urban cities with a concentration of world class academics is likely to improve the availability a startup has for acquiring high skilled workers such as researchers, data analysts, engineers, etc. We can calculate the distance a startup is from a university, and see if that leads to a greater level of innovation. This data can be pulled from QS Top University and other data sources, although there are not many databases that list the exact GPS location of each of these universities.

Although the Bernard (2016) dataset had information on universities, it did not have the exact longitude and latitude of these universities. This is unfortunate as this information can then allow us to create an IV that can be used to understand the causal mechanisms that are present in this data. For example, the distance a startup is away from a university or urban setting can be used as an IV to understand the degree to which the startup is ’plugged-in’ to the local research pool. Of course, it is unclear which independent variable that this theoretical IV would be most correlated with (perhaps it could be brain power, however this is unlikely because university graduates are not guaranteed to work in the same area), however it may have been worth the consideration if the scraping were feasible

Other data that can be potentially scraped could be the social media presence and/or the public perception of these startups. It is reasonable to assume that the more successful a startup is, the greater their funding for advertising, SEO, and marketing would become. If this assumption holds, we can attempt to proxy this by analyzing their social media presence and activity. What can be more effective could be to attempt to scrape public opinion data, which may provide key insights into the success of a company. The clear choice for this kind of scraping project would be to scrape public opinion data from twitter, yelp, and other sites where customer engagement is gathered.

Potential challenges¶

Scraping these potential data sources however is a highly ambitious task that would require weeks, if not months of data scraping. As far as this author understands, it is possible to scrape most of these data at any time. There are immediate challenges for some of these datasets, for example Yahoo! Finance only lists companies that are publicly traded or are unicorn startups, and does not provide estimates on the valuation of some of the smaller companies in this list. This could lead to sampling bias in regression testing down the line, as we can not comment on the valuation of the newer (by 2014 standard) startups or the lesser valued companies that would not be listed on Yahoo. Furthermore, because the financial statements of smaller private companies are not legally required to be disclosed to the public, and because there would be less data available for smaller private startups, estimating the value of these companies could be challenging. It is possible however to find enough estimates by scraping multiple websites and comparing similar companies, and could perhaps be explored further in a future research project.

The potential challenges associated with many university related websites is that many universities will not include information about the precise geographic location of each university. This information is likely in each university websites, which may require a web crawler or other tools to access. Because this approach would require a more 'decentralized' approach to scraping, which would likely require further researching and technical skills to accomplish. Furthermore, with websites like QS Top University there are issues with the terms of service that do not allow users to easily access the data using HTML scraping techniques. After some research, QS does seem to have some API, however this would require API tokens (Which I currently do not possess).

Finally, for social media presence and/or the public opinion data would be further challenging to scrape and analyze. Although twitter has an API based data scraping options, with the amount of potentially misleading data that can exist and the difficulty in cleaning such a dataset in a way that can be merged with this project's current data would be difficult to manage. Because all of the following projects seem far too ambitious at this stage of the project, instead this project will focus on scraping simpler datasets that can still provide useful information that can determine the likelihood of success of a startup.

Scraping data from a website¶

For this project, a dataset that is scrapable that is a potentially useful determinant for the likelihood of success for a startup is the tax incentives provided by each region for R&D companies. Many industries, such as the biotech sector or technology sector, is deemed to be valuable to the innovative output as well as economic well being of a country. Many wealthier countries in the world will therefore attempt to encourage startups in certain industries to cultivate innovation and technological output. As a result, it can be valuable to understand the general tax incentive programs that are available in each state.

According to EY, North American states which are offering R&D tax incentives programs in 2014 are US and Canada. Although Mexico has since introduced an R&D program in 2017, because this is out of the range that is made available on the Kaggle dataset it does not qualify for analysis. An interesting direction this project can be taken can be to focus on Mexico and the Carribean, and perhaps use a diff-in-diff analysis to understand the impact the tax incentives program has had on Mexico's startup economy. However, for this project, we will be scraping tax incentives programs in the US and Canada and see the impact these laws have on their local startup economies.

The R&D Tax credits by US states data was scraped from Alvarez and Marsal website, and Canadian provincial data was scraped from the Government of Canada's website.

The only source which lists Quebec's tax credit rate is on the SR&ED website, however the site blocks the 'inspect element' feature (It even does not allow copy and pasting). Therefore, since this is the only province which has these restrictions, it seemed necessary to manually add the 14% tax credit that is offered by the Quebecois government.

Merge the Scraped Dataset/adding a new dataset¶

For this section, we need to find a way to merge the scraped tax credit dataset to the existing startup dataset. Although the American startups have clearly denoted state codes that can be matched to the scraped dataset, the Canadian dataset only lists cities and regions. This is an immediate challenge, as many of these observations will list only cities or regions without their associated provincial name, which means there will be merging issues with the scraped dataset, which only includes provincial name. To avoid this, a new dataset will be imported that can merge with the existing dataset to give an accurate provincial category, allowing it to be merged successfully. On simplemaps.com there was a free dataset that contained a list of Canadian cities with a population over 1000. There is a slight assumption in using this dataset, as it assumes that every startup in Canada are located in bigger urban centers. However with the results of Project two, this assumption will probably lead to the highest level of matching for a publicly available dataset.

The following code will also be using the rapidfuzz library to merge some of the city names in the existing dataset to the cities in the imported dataset. Without this, almost 1000 observations would have subtle spelling errors that this program will not know how to interpret, and would be forced to be dropped. Once this merging process is done, every Canadian observation will have a new 'state' code, which will list the province

Finally, the scraped dataset will be able to be merged.

Visualizing the scraped Dataset¶

Now that the NA_SU dataframe has been updated to include the tax credits program that is offered by their local government, we can now visualize this data the same way we have done thus far. Because it is difficult to understand the relationship between tax policies and geographic location, it may be useful to view this in a map form. The map below shows Canada as largely being homogenous in terms of their tax credit, offering around the same range across provinces around 10%. US states on the otherhand have far greater variation, with many states having tax rates 0% from coast to coast to New York's absurd 50% tax credit rate program. With previous maps, we noted that many startups are centered around New York, regardless of industry or the age of the company. This map can show that, with some of the newer startups in this dataset, the New York government's high tax incentives program could have been an even greater motivating factor for startups to begin their operations.

Interestingly, Arkansas is noticeably red in this map. According to the Arkansas Economic Development Commission, targetted businesses in agriculture, biotechnology, IT, and transportation logistics, as well as "qualified research" that leads to innovations in technologies, receive a tax credit for 33% of qualified R&D salaries each year for five years. This policy is likely an attempt by the Arkansas government to make their state attractive to entrepreneurs and researchers to improve the economy of their state. With a newer startup data and further research into Arkansas' tax credit policy, this too could prove to be an interesting case study of the effectiveness of tax incentives.

However, it must be noted that there is chance that the long term impact RD incentive programs have are not felt in 2014, as it may take longer than expected for companies to take advantage of these local government tax benefits. To understand the true impact of a program like this, it might be useful to think about doing a diff-in-diff model to understand the effect a positive tax ’shock’ has on a regions startup market.

OLS regression¶

In the current NA_SU dataframe, it is unlikely that the economic relationship between the x variables and the y variables are 'linear'. The fact is, for much of the data present in this dataset, there is reason to believe that it suffers greatly from incomplete information. Immediately noticeable in our dataset is that there are a large number of zeroes that are included for key variables, most notably the valuation of startups (dependent variable) is problematic as there are too many zero values. This is extended further into the total_acquired_price variable, which has many zero entries. The most likely cause of this is that the true value of a startup or the exact price they have been acquired for are likely unknown to the public and the creators of the Kaggle dataset handled missing entries by estimating these values as zero. Furthermore, the num_miles variable can be prone to selection bias, as it is unclear how this data had been collected by the creators of the database. If these variable were scrapped from social media or other websites, it is likely to be biased towards startups that have significant marketing power or a capable social media/HR team that can promote every major or minor accompishment from online.

In economic language, for the majority of private companies (especially the lesser known ones that go unnoticed by the general public), the data suffers from information asymmetry. Using the valuation of startups as an example, although there are certainly differences between the average startup when compared to the most profitable 'startups' such as Google, Facebook, and General Motors, it is unlikely that the valuation of a company can ever be zero. \cite{miloud} discusses alternative methods that can evaluate a startup even if they do not have the necessary accounting information to determine the present value of future cash of private corporations. These include the market and industry characteristics as well as the value of a startup's network. Assuming all startups in this dataset have a founder, every startup should have some value that is associated with at least the founder. They would have some level of education, some innovative idea, and would operate within some industry that has some inherent value associated with it. Therefore, it is impossible for any of our observations to have zero value. We can also extend a similar reasoning to fill the empty values for network size with 1, as every startup will have a network of at least one founder.

As mentioned in \cite{ratzinger} and \cite{baum}, we know that many of the independent variables that are used for this regression are in fact corroborated by the literature. \cite{ratzinger} discusses the importance of education of the founder and the greater number of patents that come from a higher educated network. \cite{baum} talks in detail about the importance of network size and strategic alliances that can help at least biotech startups from obtaining patents as well. This model will however take additional precautions to avoid the aforementioned issues of non-linearity between brain power and network size with the valuation of the company. Brain power can be assumed to have diminishing returns, and therefore the non-linear relationship can be addressed by including a squared term for brain power in the final regression results. As will be demonstrated in a simple OLS plot of network size and valuation in the next section, it becomes apparent that including log values for network size is important in improving our interpretation of the coefficients as well as improving the overall fit of the model to our data. After accounting for the non linear relationship between the variables, the coefficients for brain_power were statistically signficant at 0.013 and log(network_size) was statistically significant at 0.478.

The economic intuition behind including tax credit rates in this regression is that it controls for some of the geographic differences (tax credits are offered from local governments only), and can be assumed to incentivize entrepreneurs from creating startups. Although tax_credit_convert were moderately significant at 0.025, the coefficient was not statistically significant. This can be due to the fact that country fixed effects were used for the models 3 and 4, and therefore much of the variation had already been accounted for.

The four regressions use a greater number of x variables as determinants for log valuation. As mentioned in the first project, including established startups could possibly skew our findings as they will have a value that most startups (including unicorns) could not match. Therefore, instead of using the startup dataframe, a new dataframe was created that did not include the established startups. Removing the Unicorn startups could be problematic however, as the new dataframe would then be forced to be 'truncated' and upperbound. However, we can use the unicorn dummy to do a very simplistic dummy regression to compare unicorns and non unicorns in the new millennia.

On average, we noticed that a unicorn startup founded after 1990 had an average valuation 298.6% higher than the mean valuation of a non-unicorn startup. However, this regression is far too simplistic to give us an effective understanding of the differences between unicorn and non unicorn startups. The results are here only to demonstrate simply the existing differences between the two groups. For the final regression, more complex models will be used and both types of startups will be included.

The first regression is the simplest, only using three x variables: number of milestones, brain power, and network size. The simple regression has the following equation:

$$ \log(\text{Valuation}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Milestones} + \beta_2 \text{BrainPower} + \beta_3 \text{NetworkSize} + \epsilon $$

As predicted, other than tax credit rates - which has a good reason for being statistically insignificant - every variable demonstrates a high level of statistical significance. The Intercept has a coefficient of 7.713, implying that a startup that has 0 for all of the X variables would have on average a log valuation of 7.713. Though this is not information is not as useful to us, the gradually increasing intercept values with the increasing R2 values can be interpreted as the regressions accounting for non-linearity with each new model.

The simple model, which assumes linearity for brain power and network size, may be statistically significant, however are likely biased as a result of the assumptions. The second model improves upon this by including the ’non-linear’ model as well as controlling for Status and Time fixed effects. Though number of milestones loses much of it’s significance, a greater increase in economic significance for the log network size is noticed. All the values remain statistically highly significant. Every variable is statistically significant, however the network_size has a very low economic significance and the lower $R^2$ value indicates that the model is a poor fit overall. This poor fit likely comes because the relationship between the x variables and the log valuation is non-linear. As previously mentioned, there is likely diminishing returns on the average quality of education received by the network for startups.

The second regression attempts to account for a similar non-linear relationship between log valuation, average quality of education, and network size. This is similar to a Mincer Earnings Equation first published in 1974 (Heckman et al., 6), which proposes that the log earnings of an individual has a non-linear relationship with level of market experience and years of schooling, as well as controlling for status and time fixed effects.

$$ \log(\text{Valuation}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Milestones} + \beta_2 \text{BrainPower} + \beta_3 \text{BrainPower}^2 + \beta_4 \log (\text{NetworkSize}) + \text{TimeFixedEffects} + \text{YearFixedEffects} + \gamma_1 \text{Status} + \epsilon $$

This increases the value of $R^2$ greatly, improving the overall fit of the model. It should be noted that as expected, $\beta_3$ is negative and statistically significant, however is not economically signficant as the value is very small.

The third model controls for the potential variation by industry and country, in addition to controlling for the benefits of having the tax incentives program in place. Surprisingly, this value is not significant, which can be caused by a few reasons. The primary cause of these issues is most likely due to the country fixed effects, which is a variable that is multicolinear with the tax incentives program, as both are geographically locked. Otherwise, this regression has slightly higher economic significance for all other variables, with log network size increasing by 0.084. This implies that after controling for status, category, founded year, and country fixed effects, an 10% increase in a startups network size will on average increase your valuation by 6.67%, which is economically signficant.

The fourth model interacts the brain power of a company with the network size in addition to the same controls and variables. These were selected as an interaction term, $\text{BrainPower}*\log(\text{NetworkSize})$, as a large network size can be further benefitted if the majority of the members also received a higher quality education. The final regression's formula will be the following:

$$ \log(\text{Valuation}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Milestones} + \beta_2 \text{BrainPower} + \beta_3 \text{BrainPower}^2 + \beta_4 \log (\text{NetworkSize}) + \beta_5 \text{BrainPower}*\log(\text{NetworkSize}) + $$$$ \text{YearFixedEffects} + \gamma_1 \text{Category} + \gamma_2 \text{Country} + \gamma_3 \text{Status} + \epsilon $$

Unsurprisingly, the interaction term in the fourth model remains highly significant, as it is likely a ’smarter’ network will be more useful for a startup. It is unsurprising that the inclusion of this interaction term reduces the economic significance of both the brain power and log network size variable, as the term is composed of them and is by design slightly ’multi-colinear’. After the interaction terms inclusion, a 20 percentage point change in brain power will increase the valuation of your startup by 16%, and a 10% increase in network size will increase the valuation of a startup by 4.78%, both of which seem economically significant. All the variables that were significant in the third model and the interaction term are significant in the final regression as

These results corroborate existing literature and shows that an entrepreneur with greater number of milestones, well educated individuals, and a greater network size will on average have a more successful startup that has the potential to become a Unicorn startup founder. This information can be useful for these prospective entrepreneurs who wish to be the Pale Rider on the Pale Horse that is referenced in the title of this project!

There are more sophisticated methods of evaluating a regression result than the $R^2$. Comparing the MSE of this model allows us to evaluate the qualtiy of the estimators that are used for our analysis. The value of the MSE is approximately 0.6, which means the model will not be able to predict the success of startups accurately. This is because MSE is the average of the differences between the actual log valuation (dependent variables) minus our model's prediction of Y. The formula in the case of the fourth regression will be:

$$ \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \left(Y_i - \hat{Y}_i\right)^2 \mid Y_i - \hat{Y_i} = \log(\text{valuation}_i) -(\beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Milestones}_i + \beta_2 \text{BrainPower}_i + $$$$ \beta_3 \text{BrainPower}^2_i + \beta_4 \log (\text{NetworkSize}_i) + \beta_5 \text{BrainPower}_i*\log(\text{NetworkSize}_i) + \text{YearFixedEffects}_i + \gamma_1 \text{Category}_i + \gamma_2 \text{Country}_i + \gamma_3 \text{Status}_i) $$

For us to evaluate our model and possibly obtain a new regression with a lower MSE value, we must be open to using regression methods that are beyond the OLS. In the next section, we will be experimenting with ML methods and compare the resulting MSE with the OLS regression method.

Machine Learning¶

In this section, we will be using experimental machine learning models such as regression trees, bagging, RandomForest, and boosting techniques in order to develop a more sophisticated model that can predict the change in valuation that results from changes in the determinants used in the same regression mode

Regression Trees¶

To start with regression trees, we must first understand the objective function that we will be using for the regression. The following is the function:

$$ \min_{j,s} \left[ \sum_{i: x_{i,j} \leq s, x_i \in R1} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R1})^2 + \sum_{i: x_{i,j} > s, x_i \in R2} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R2})^2 \right] $$$$ \min_{tree \subset T} \sum (\hat{f}(x)-y)^2 + \alpha|\text{terminal nodes in tree}| $$

This function first chooses a variable and tries to group these variables in a way that minimizes the total MSE of the two groups that are formed. R1 and R2 are the two groups that are formed after the regression tree algorithm iterates through once. Though it looks complicated, the two summations are the MSE of each simple regression. After One Hot Encoding the relevant categorical variables, the final dataset had 72 possible variables that a regression tree could use for analysis. Without setting a maximum depth, the trees that could potentially be formed to artificially lower the MSE value are very high. Interestingly, setting a tree with maximum depth 4 has a MSE value equal to 0.6762, which is higher than the multiple regression model that was created. Creating a tree with a depth greater than 4 seemed to complicate the model far too much and lead to an over-fitting model that has lower predictive power.

To explain each rectangular section and it's interpretation, with each section that is discussed, we will be moving closer to the tree with the lowest square error. For regression tree, the first rectangular section that was selected by the algorithm was the log_network_size variable values less than or equal to 0.512. For startups with log_network_size variable values greater than 0.512, the next rectangular section was once again the log_network_size variable, which was less than or equal to 1.19. At the next depth, the section segregated the operating status startups. For startups that were not 'operating', the next tree separated startups with an interaction term less than 37794.5. This does not mean that non-operating startups are more successful, but is most likely referring to the 'IPO' or 'Acquired' status startups that will have greater valuation. The 41 Startups with a value greater than 37794.5 that remained had on average a log valuation equal to 10.222.

Though this is theoretically interesting, it yields a higher MSE value than the multivariate regression model that was designed. Now we will use the bagging model.

Bagging¶

Bagging - or Bootstrap Aggregation - does the same thing as a regression model, however it does so in a small sample of each of the data and finds the 'average' and minimized regression tree. The resulting MSE is far lower than both the multivariate regression as well as the original regression tree, with a value equal to 0.238. As observable from the $Y \hat{Y}$ plot, we can see that $Y$ and $\hat{Y}$ are grouped together well. Interestingly, there seems to be some mild truncation (a cutoff) when $Y$ is below 4. Because $Y$ is the log valuation of a company, all values above 1 should be visible in this dataset. It is unclear if these issues are caused by some error or the Bagging method. Further experimentation may be needed to understand this in detail.

Random Forest¶

The Random Forest technique further varies the answer from the bagging, as it forces the variables in each tree to be different than the other trees. As a result, we would be able to judge which variables are more important than the others.

We can use the importance matrix that is derived as a result of this to find the most valuable determinants in our dataset in determining our variable. Every one of the independent variables included in the final model of our regression was significant, including tax credit rates, which was found more important, at least in terms of reducing error, than the number of milestones! This further validates the existing theories that this paper had operated with.

Comparing results with OLS regression¶

As mentioned, the bagging method was the only ML method that seemed to lower the value of the MSE. Although using the Machine Learning model sacrifices some of the intuition of the OLS regression, it is quite an effective tool at making predictions. Compared to the Regression Tree, though the interpretation itself was simple enough, when evaluating purely on MSE, the OLS regression results seemed easier to interpret and more applicable by comparison.

Conclusion¶

In this paper, we measured the effect that number of milestones, brain power, network size, and tax credit rates have on the log valuation of a startup. The analysis uses the data collected by Cirtautus (2020) and try to understand the valuation of startups that were not considered ’estab- lished’. By doing this, we could understand modern trends and Unicorn startups that economists and venture capitalists of today are interested in understanding. By focusing on these variables, we add to the existing literature on this subject by trying to create a generalized form for both the network size and brain power.

By selecting the interaction term, we found that a one unit increase in brain power * log network size leads to a 0.8% increase in the valuation of your company. As seen in the Machine Learning section, the interaction term can be surprisingly large, as brain power is between 0 and 100 and the network size of a company can be quite large. However, there could be more interaction terms that have not been considered in this paper that can be investigated further in the future.

Upon finishing this paper, future research should primarily focus on the use of IVs to test for causality as well as developing a 2SLS. A valid IV seems possible, as startup headquarters have geographical coordinates associated with them. One possible direction that future research can take is calculating the spherical distance between the startup headquarters and the fund headquarters where they received funding from. We can use this measure to understand the changes in one of the X variables that are correlated with the IV. Other potential IVs, as mentioned in the web scraping section of Project Two, is the possibility of measuring the spherical distance between startups and university campuses. In the same section, there is some discussion on some of the challenges of using these variables. However, with greater time and further research, it seems possible to uncover a valid IV that others are unaware of.

A Difference in Difference analysis, although it can be interesting, will be difficult to do with the current dataset as it is not panel data. However, if a startup dataset is found that is a panel dataset, we can immediately find the differences that happen the moment a exogenous shock of tax credit rates are introduced. This would give us a better understanding of how a tax credit rate can potentially improve the startup economy in a specific location.

As shown by Baum et al. (2000), Network size is statistically significant even outside of the biotech sector. However, some of the limitations of this is that the variables created as estimates were different than those specified in the literature. For example Baum et al. (2000) had detailed alliance, rival, and efficiency variables that were completely simplified for our own analysis. In future research, data can potentially be scraped to try to create variables that are similar to those used in the results of Baum et al. (2000). Most of the other literature was corroborated in our findings.

The main implication that was found is that the quality of education received by founding team members, their numbers, and the number of milestones reached by the startup were most important determinants for startup valuation, at least according to the OLS regression model that was created for this paper. The results of the ML section shows that each of the variables that were predicted to be significant were. However, many of these factors may seem trivial to some observers. Still, by using data analytics tools to investigate this subject has shown that even a deeply flawed dataset such as this was able to effectively support existing theories
